=========================================
C++ STL SET - INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is set?
---------------
- std::set is an associative container in STL.
- Stores UNIQUE elements only.
- Elements are always stored in SORTED order (ascending by default).

Example:
set<int> s;

Insert:
10, 20, 10, 30

Stored:
10 20 30   (duplicates removed + sorted)

-----------------------------------------

2. Internal Implementation
--------------------------
- Implemented using SELF-BALANCING BINARY SEARCH TREE
  (usually Red-Black Tree)

Properties:
✔ Balanced BST
✔ O(log n) operations
✔ Sorted order maintained automatically

-----------------------------------------

3. Key Properties
-----------------
✔ Stores unique elements only
✔ Always sorted
✔ No indexing allowed
✔ Bidirectional iterators supported

-----------------------------------------

4. Complexity
-------------
insert()   -> O(log n)
erase()    -> O(log n)
find()     -> O(log n)
count()    -> O(log n)
size()     -> O(1)
empty()    -> O(1)

-----------------------------------------

5. Why set is used?
-------------------
✔ Maintain sorted data
✔ Remove duplicates automatically
✔ Fast search (O(log n))

-----------------------------------------

6. set vs unordered_set
-----------------------

set:
- Sorted
- O(log n)

unordered_set:
- Unsorted
- Average O(1)
- Worst O(n)

Use set when:
✔ order matters
✔ need range queries

-----------------------------------------

7. set vs vector
----------------

vector:
- Duplicates allowed
- Not sorted (unless sorted manually)
- O(n) search

set:
- Unique elements
- Always sorted
- O(log n) operations

-----------------------------------------

8. Iterator In set
------------------
- Bidirectional iterator
- Used for traversal

Example:
for(auto it : s)

-----------------------------------------

9. Important Operations
-----------------------

✔ insert(x)
✔ erase(x)
✔ find(x)
✔ count(x)
✔ lower_bound(x)
✔ upper_bound(x)
✔ begin()
✔ end()

-----------------------------------------

10. lower_bound vs upper_bound
------------------------------

lower_bound(x):
- First element >= x

upper_bound(x):
- First element > x

Example:
set = {10, 20, 30}

lower_bound(20) -> 20
upper_bound(20) -> 30

-----------------------------------------

11. erase types
---------------

1. erase(value)
   removes element

2. erase(iterator)
   removes single element

3. erase(range)
   removes multiple elements

-----------------------------------------

12. Why no indexing?
--------------------
- set is not stored in contiguous memory
- it is a tree structure
- so s[i] is not allowed

-----------------------------------------

13. When to use set?
---------------------
✔ need sorted unique values
✔ need fast search
✔ need ordered traversal
✔ range queries required

Avoid when:
✗ duplicates needed
✗ random access needed
✗ performance critical (use unordered_set instead)

-----------------------------------------

14. Real-world uses
-------------------
✔ Finding duplicates
✔ Sorted unique elements
✔ Leaderboards (sorted IDs)
✔ Range queries
✔ Graph algorithms

-----------------------------------------

